<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>"ğŸ‘ğŸ¿".length    // returns 4
"ğŸ‡¨ğŸ‡¦".length    // returns 4
"ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ‘§â€ğŸ‘§".length    // lol returns 11 (2*4 for each person + 3 connectors)
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If you type this (in April 2016) in something like Atom (or even Atomâ€™s dev tools) though,
youâ€™ll notice something weird. Instead of getting a black thumbs up, or the Canadian flag, you get this (I had to highlight the Canadian flag bit, because the glyphs are white):</p>

<p><img width="129" alt="a yellow thumbs up with a dark brown square; two boxes, each with the letters C and A; 4 separate heads in a line" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1369170/14193347/def54478-f758-11e5-95ca-bc8b5988874c.png" /></p>

<p>Whoaaaa, whatâ€™s going on there? (This is a trick question. Iâ€™ma tell you whatâ€™s going on there.)</p>

<p>The <a href="http://unicode.org/reports/tr51/#Flags">flags</a> are built around a weird (and annoying to implement) rule: the
surrogate pairs (called <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">regional indicators</code>) spell out the country code (so
ğŸ‡¨ğŸ‡¦ is actually <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">[C][A]</code>). Skin colours are similar, but a little simpler:
theyâ€™re made out a special emoji <a href="http://unicode.org/reports/tr51/#Subject_Emoji_Modifiers">base</a> + one of the 6 special colour <a href="http://unicode.org/reports/tr51/#Emoji_Modifiers_Table">modifiers</a>. The couples/multi
families are a <a href="http://www.unicode.org/emoji/charts/emoji-zwj-sequences.html">sequence</a> of characters, that together make one emoji.</p>

<h2 style="border-left-color:#a77be3;">ğŸ‘¾ So what does Chrome do?</h2>
<p>Okay, cool! We figured out what code units we need for ğŸ‡¨ğŸ‡¦, now, letâ€™s figure
out how to render them!</p>

<p>First, Chrome uses a text shaper called <a href="http://harfbuzz.org/">Harfbuzz</a>. Text shapers
take Unicode code points and convert them to glyph indices (basically saying â€œyouâ€™re going to 
have to draw glyphs 23 and 74â€) â€“ and guess what we have! Unicode
code points! The text shaper is the one that knows how to look at this stream
of code units and surrogate pairs and figure out which are standalone, which
are weirdo flags, and which are modifiers. Once itâ€™s done with it, it comes
up with the glyph and the position where to draw it. If you think about a couple,
ğŸ‘©â€â¤ï¸â€ğŸ‘©, all surrogate pairs need to be drawn on
top of each other, so that the spacing around the final glyph adds up.</p>

<p>This glyph and its size/position eventually goes to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skia_Graphics_Engine">Skia</a>,
Chromeâ€™s graphics engine. It is the one that paints the right thing on the screen (<a href="https://code.google.com/p/chromium/codesearch#chromium/src/third_party/skia/src/ports/SkFontHost_mac.cpp&amp;l=1257">here</a> is that code).</p>

<h2 style="border-left-color:#5b86f7;">ğŸ–Œ What about fonts?</h2>

<p>Fonts, boy, themâ€™s a pickle. Thereâ€™s basically one font per platform that
actually knows how to draw emoji (unless you went out of your way to
install extra ones). All the other fonts just rent the emoji from it.
These fonts are AppleColorEmoji (OS X), Segoe UI Symbol/Emoji (Windows),
NotoColorEmoji (Android) and I donâ€™t know what Linux does, but itâ€™s probably
black and white and who cares, I hear you can run bash on Windows now. Iâ€™m going to keep talking about the Apple font, because thatâ€™s
the code path I worked on in Chrome, but Windows works very similarly.</p>

<p>So letâ€™s say you have this:</p>

<div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nt">&lt;p</span> <span class="na">style=</span><span class="s">"font-family: 'Comic Sans MS', sans-serif;"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>ğŸ˜»<span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
